SIMPLE: solemnize
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Solemnize
<hw>Sol"em*nize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Solemnized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Solemnizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>solemniser</ets>, <ets>sollemniser</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To perform with solemn or ritual ceremonies, or according to legal
forms.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Baptism to be administered in one place, and marriage
<qex>solemnized</qex> in another.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To dignify or honor by ceremonies; to
celebrate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their choice nobility and flowers . . . ⟦br⟧
Met from all parts to <qex>solemnize</qex> this feast.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make grave, serious, and reverential.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wordsworth was <qex>solemnizzed</qex> and elevated by this his
first look on Yarrow.</q> <rj><qau>J. C. Shairp.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every Israelite . . . arose, <qex>solemnized</qex> his face,
looked towards Jerusalem . . . and prayed.</q> <rj><qau>L.
Wallace.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Solemnize</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Solemnize
<hw>Sol"em*nize</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Solemnization.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though spoused, yet wanting wedlock's <qex>solemnize</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Solemnizer</ent>⟦br⟧
